.SH DISPLAY SYSTEMS

.PP
\fBalsavol\fP supports several display types selected using the \(aq-t\(aq option or \(aqDisplayType\(aq config file entry. These are:
.PP
.in +2

.TP
.B term
display in terminal

.TP
.B dialog
display using whichever of zenity, qarma or yad is found on the system

.TP
.B zenity
display using the \(aqzenity\(aq dialog application

.TP
.B qarma
display using the \(aqqarma\(aq dialog application

.TP
.B yad
display using the \(aqyad\(aq dialog application

.TP
.B wish
display using the tcl \(aqwish\(aq shell

.TP
.B pterm
display using a popup terminal using one of urxvt, xterm, aterm, mlterm or st

.TP
.B urxvt
display using a \(aqurxvt\(aq as a popup window
.in

.PP
alsavol\(aqs default behavior is to display a slider bar in the terminal/console. This slider can be moved using keys or the mousewheel. 
.PP
If \(aqdialog\(aq. \(aqzenity\(aq, \(aqqarma\(aq, \(aqyad\(aq or \(aqwish\(aq modes are used then a popup window is created using one of those applications. Keystrokes listed below in \(aqTERMINAL KEYS\(aq are not honored in these modes, and the resulting display is entirely controlled by the dialog system. 
.PP
\(aqpterm\(aq and \(aqurxvt\(aq are modes where alsavol displays itself within a dedicated terminal window. In this mode \(aqTERMINAL KEYS\(aq are honored, and there are some unique options, like urxvt\(aqs \(aqkuake hotkey\(aq feature.
.SH TERMINAL KEYS

.PP
In \(aqterm\(aq or \(aqpterm\(aq mode alsavol is controlable with the following keys
.nf
.ft CW

.RS
.EX

decrease volume:
  * left arrow
  * <
  * ,
  * \-
  * mousewheel 

increase volume:
  * right arrow
  * >
  * .
  * +
  * mousewheel 

next sound card:
  * tab
  * home
  * down arrow
  * ]
  * n

prev sound card:
  * up arrow
  * [
  * p

mute:
  * m

exit app:
  * q
  * escape
  * delete
  * backspace
  * end
.RE
.EE
.fi
.in
.ad b
.nop  
.PP
The \(aqvolume up\(aq, \(aqvolume down\(aq and \(aqmute\(aq media keys may also be honored.
.SH CARD ORDER

.PP
There are a number of config-file and command-line settings that control which sound-cards are displayed, and in what order. These are applied at different stages of processing the sound-card list.
.PP
.in +2

.TP
.B \(aqIgnoreCards\(aq or \(aq-ignore\(aq or \(aq-I\(aq
This is a comma-separated list of cards to ignore. It\(aqs applied when we gather a list of cards from the ALSA API. \fBalsavol\fP already has an internal list of card names to ignore, consisting of "hw,oss,shm,arcam_av,sysdefault,default" and the user-supplied names are added to this ignore list.
.in

.PP
.in +2

.TP
.B \(aqCardOrder\(aq or \(aq-order\(aq or \(aq-O\(aq
This is a comma-separated list of shell-style pattern matches that allows setting the order in which cards are displayed to the user. If a card is not listed in this order then it is not displayed, which is another way to ignore a card. And Example of use might be:
.in

.nf
.ft CW

.RS
.EX

CardOrder=*Corsair VOID*,*Headset,*
.RE
.EE
.fi
.in
.ad b
.nop  
.PP
Which would display cards in the order: Card with "Corsair VOID" in it\(aqs name, all cards ending in "Headset", then anything else
.PP
N.B. if the 
.na

.nf
.ft CW
*
.fi
.ft P

.ad n
.nop is missed from the end of the card order, then the remaining cards will not be displayed.
.PP
There is also the 
.na

.nf
.ft CW
\-c
.fi
.ft P

.ad n
.nop and 
.na

.nf
.ft CW
\-card
.fi
.ft P

.ad n
.nop command-line options. These are exclusively used with the \(aq-set\(aq option to set the value of a device\(aqs volume level without displaying a user interface. They take either a full ALSA card name, or a card index (\(aq0\(aq for the first card).
.SH WINDOW SETTINGS

.PP
Different display types support windows that \(aqstick to desktop\(aq or are transparent, or borderless. Some of these features are natively supported by the applications, while others are set using the \(aqwmctrl\(aq command-line application, and will not work if that\(aqs not installed. These features are activated using \(aqPopupFlags\(aq in the config file, or by individual options on the command-line. The available features are:
.PP
.in +2

.TP
.B above
keep window above all other windows, supported using 
.na

.nf
.ft CW
wmctrl
.fi
.ft P

.ad n
.nop for all display types (except obviously terminal)
.in

.PP
.in +2

.TP
.B sticky
keep window above all other windows, supported using 
.na

.nf
.ft CW
wmctrl
.fi
.ft P

.ad n
.nop for all display types (except obviously terminal)
.in

.PP
.in +2

.TP
.B transparent
give window a pseudo-transparent background. Supported for \(aqpterm\(aq display type with terminals mlterm, aterm, and urxvt
.in

.PP
.in +2

.TP
.B tr
short name for \(aqtransparent\(aq
.in

.PP
.in +2

.TP
.B borderless
display window without the usual window-manager title bar and border. Supported for \(aqpterm\(aq display type with terminals aterm, mlterm but not urxvt due to a bug in urxvt that makes borderless windows \(aqno input\(aq
.in

.PP
.in +2

.TP
.B bl
short name for \(aqborderless\(aq
.in

.SH WINDOW STYLES

.PP
The \(aq-style\(aq command-line option and \(aqWindowStyle\(aq config setting select a display style for the \(aqterm\(aq and \(aqpterm\(aq display types. Available styles are:
.PP
.in +2

.TP
.B basic
a 2-line display style where the control slider is displayed under the card name
.in

.PP
.in +2

.TP
.B 2line
another name for \(aqbasic\(aq style
.in

.PP
.in +2

.TP
.B 1line
a compact style where everything is displayed on 1 line, with the card name before the control slider
.in

.PP
.in +2

.TP
.B compact
a compact style where everything is displayed on 1 line, with the card name overlaid on the control slider
.in

.PP
.in +2

.TP
.B pterm
a style where the card name is not displayed, usually used for \(aqpterm\(aq display types, where the card name is instead set as the window title
.in
